chance to make their voices heard and to reshape the landscape of
political possibility. Democracy by Petition traces the
explosion and expansion of petitioning across the North American
continent. Indigenous tribes in Canada, free Blacks from Boston to
the British West Indies, Irish canal workers in Indiana, and
Hispanic settlers in territorial New Mexico all used petitions to
make claims on those in power. Petitions facilitated the extension
of suffrage, the decline of feudal land tenure, and advances in
