@article{Epstein2013,
abstract = {Among political scientists, not only is it uncontroversial to say that judges seek to etch their political values into law; it would be near heresy to suggest otherwise. And yet this article does just that because research conducted by scholars (mostly outside of political science) has demonstrated that the policy goal is not the only motivation; it may not even be dominant for many judges. The evidence is now so strong that it poses a serious challenge to the extremely (un)realist(ic) conception of judicial behavior that has dominated the study of law and legal institutions for generations. In addition to reviewing this evidence, we offer a more realistic conception of judicial motivations and suggest how different approaches to the study of courts can contribute to this new avenue of research.},
annote = {Epstein and Knight book notes: offer a plethora of anecdotes and summary statistics about judicial decision making. It is informative about how the supreme court makes decisions, but does nothing to resolve dominant models of decision making. Few of their examples or data are not equally plausible outcomes of different theories of decision-making. 


Their argument that judges are rational actors if frequency assumed. Each section takes the general form: 
“a [rational] justice would have no reason not to [act rationally]” where the act is something judges are well known to do frequently. “How common is this? It is common.” Thus, the data show that judges are rational actors.


This logic does little to discriminate between observationally equivalent outcomes plausibly due to any number of different theories of judicial behavior. 


Rational choices are understood to be sophisticated and frequently change. Quotes from internal memos suggest these changes are made in light of information about the preferences of others. Do these memos lack reasonings and arguments? The authors never entertain the notion that justices may be convinced. 


In addition to new preferences, new choices are often introduced/invented. In this context, how are we to understand rational action related to stable preferences on issues that are entirely new. Can a justice have fixed preferences relative to an issues one has never thought about. For example, in the case used to introduce the argument, the NAACP amicus brief suggested a new potential standard of review. Epstein and Knight first use the positions announced by justices at the cert hearing as evidence of original positions / sincere preferences. They take the change from these ‘original.sincere' preferences to the NAACP standard as strategic accommodation to form a majority. However, they later note how these statements are ambiguous and may be strategic. All of this is taken to be evidence that judges are strategic actors. Unfortunately, Epstein and Knight fail to escape from the tautology of preferences and actions. 


They use the same example to illustrate why a justice may select an outcome other than her most preferred when her most preferred is in the minority. Justices may settle on some middle ground or set the issue aside by ruling on a different issue. However, in order for the example to illustrate their point, at least one justice must be assumed to prioritize jurisprudence over policy. If judges can rationally prefer jurisprudence as their top preference, and it is not merely a restrain imposed by the need to maintain legitimacy (as they suggest), then what does it mean to say judges are rational? 


They discuss at length the strategic reasons for one justice to make suggestions others, including to author of the opinion when one is deserting (pg93), but the rational for the opinion writer to grant the request is simply “giving Brennan a small victory in a case otherwise decided against his interests.” Why? 


Ultimately, with every page introducing a new layer of external or internal context which might change what is strategic, the level of sophisticated decision-making, writing, learning, bargaining, seems impossible to model as a game. 


There is much emphasis on how much judges will sacrifice to assemble a majority opinion and thus establish the ‘law of the land,” which implies that law matters. 


Efforts toward moderation and unanimity are characterized as aimed at reducing substantive backlash from “external political actors.” But if this is the end, what good does a unanimous decisions in Brown v. Board do over a 5-4? 


The authors concede significant ground on the use of a rational choice framework. Judges lack key information and sometimes prefer legal principles to material policy victories, choice spaces change in the course of deliberation and innovative reasoning, and decision-making context is “shaped by rules, norms, and conventions,” which are uncertain and also change over time. 


Interesting events are shoe-horned into the rational choice framework. A mild dissenting rebuke is considered a “sanction” for violating an informal norm of the court and thus explaining why we have not seen the norm violated since. (120)


While there was clearly gaming on behalf of Burger in Roe, Notes on 130 look much more like persuasion and reserved judgement than gaming.},
author = {Epstein, Lee and Knight, Jack},
